    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3109869417" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3109869417" />
    <a title="Daniel Corey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/23317586-daniel-corey"><img alt="Daniel Corey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1590386154p2/23317586.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3109869417?book_show_action=true">May 03, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Daniel Corey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Daniel Corey" href="/user/show/23317586-daniel-corey">Daniel Corey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3109869417" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17208788581683132144">A completely fresh and contemporary take on Dracula? Sign me up!<br/><br/>Children of the Night is a book that defies expectations and genre boundaries. Sure, on it’s surface it’s a horror novel. But it’s also part medical thriller, part globe-trotting action adventure, and part historical account of Romania during the chaotic overthrow of its leader in the early 1990s. It all combines to make a really interesting stew, giving us a unique spin on the vampire genre. <br/><br/>At its heart, this is a story about an A</span>
  <span id="freeText17208788581683132144" style="display:none">A completely fresh and contemporary take on Dracula? Sign me up!<br /><br />Children of the Night is a book that defies expectations and genre boundaries. Sure, on it’s surface it’s a horror novel. But it’s also part medical thriller, part globe-trotting action adventure, and part historical account of Romania during the chaotic overthrow of its leader in the early 1990s. It all combines to make a really interesting stew, giving us a unique spin on the vampire genre. <br /><br />At its heart, this is a story about an American doctor doing overseas work with orphaned children in Romania. She falls head over heels for a baby in her care, decides to adopt him, bring him back to the US, and discovers that he has an ultra rare condition that has some very interesting reactions to blood transfusions. Hmmmm ... wonder why? The kicker: this baby’s condition could be the key to curing cancer and AIDS!<br /><br />This leads to a really cool concept: trying to explain vampires and their need for human blood scientifically. And I mean SCIENTIFICALLY. Hope you have your PhD., because there are a few chapters in here so full of insane medical jargon that you’ll be lucky to understand a handful of words per page (Simmons, we get it. You’re smart. Quit showing off lol). Thankfully, that doesn’t persist throughout the whole book, and you can get the gist of what’s going on fairly easily. <br /><br />Without spoiling anything, the book takes several turns leading back to Romania, forcing our hero doctor to confront the vampire legend and the biggest bad of all, Count Dracula. And there is also a returning character from Summer of Night: Mike O’Rourke, now a priest with a wild side. Danger is his middle name. He’s definitely my favorite character in here. It was awesome to see how he turned out as an adult.<br /><br />The best part of this book is a series of chapters Simmons titles “Dreams of Blood And Iron”. Think Dracula doing a reality TV style series of confessionals where he recounts (in gruesome detail) all the atrocities he’s committed in his lifetime. Fascinating and brutal, these sections are worth the price of admission alone. <br /><br />Overall, this was a really enjoyable book. I found it to be an effective mix of old world vampire lore and modern day storytelling. I did have a few gripes, though. As I mentioned before, Simmons does tend to get carried away with things like medical jargon and the layout of Romanian cities (the amount of Romanian streets he name-checks in this is ridiculous). Also, there are a few plot twists surrounding one particular character that created substantial confusion for me and raised a lot of questions, and the ending got a bit far-fetched (you’ll definitely need to suspend your disbelief). <br /><br />Overall though, I really enjoyed this. It was a lot different than I was expecting, and a breath of fresh air in many regards. And I have to applaud Simmons for doing a ton of research for this novel and for trying extremely hard to put a drastically different spin on the vampire genre. <br /><br />4/5 stars.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17208788581683132144" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


